we exhausted our neighborhood search.
Continual learning (CL) is the problem of learning a sequence of tasks while retaining
knowledge from previous tasks. However, typical CL methods involve prefixed architectures
leading to limited model capacity when data distribution shifts significantly across tasks.
We introduce a mathematical framework enabling a rigorous investigation into the interplay
between model capacity and effective CL. We derive the necessary conditions for CL solution
and prove that learning only the model weights is insufficient to mitigate catastrophic for-
getting under distribution shifts. Consequently, we prove that by learning the architecture
and the weights simultaneously at each task, rather than the weights alone, we can reduce
catastrophic forgetting. However, changing architectures on the fly requires a principled
approach to knowledge transfer between weight spaces of different dimensions. We develop
a low-rank transfer mechanism to map knowledge across architectures of mismatched di-
mensions. Empirical studies across regression and classification problems, including feedfor-
ward, convolutional, and graph neural networks, demonstrate that our approach of learning
the optimal architecture and weights simultaneously yields substantially improved perfor-
mance (up to two orders of magnitude), reduced forgetting, and enhanced robustness in the
presence of noise compared with static architecture approaches.




With the advent of large-scale AI models, the computational expense of training such models has increased
drastically. In particular, training AI models efficiently often requires large-scale high-performance comput-
ing (HPC) infrastructure. Despite such drastic expenditure, these models quickly become stale because in
my real world applications, the data distribution shifts as new data gets generated due to regime change or
changes in the scientific experimentation parameters. In such scenarios, it is necesary to re-align the model
to the new data, however, this necessity presents a quandary. Naive realignment leads to a phenomenon
called catastrophic forgetting, where the model overwrites prior information. On the other hand, a complete
retraining of the model would require significant resources, a solution that is extremely unattractive.
A more viable option is continual learning (CL), where one seeks to control catastrophic forgetting. Several
works in the literature have attempted to constrain the weights of the AI model to minimize forgettin, starting
from early work on multilayer perceptrons McCloskey & Cohen (1989) to recent works on large language
models such as Luo et al. (2025); Lai et al. (2025); Biderman et al. (2024) and Lin et al. (2025). On the
other hand, and more appropriately, many recent approaches have also sought a balance between catastrophic
forgetting and the learning of new data (generalization); see, for example, Raghavan & Balaprakash (2021);
Lu et al. (2025); Lin et al. (2023). Despite demonstrated success, this is not the full story. In fact, under
mild assumptions, it has been proven that the capacity of the neural network (its ability to represent
tasks) eventually diverges if the data distribution keeps changing Chakraborty & Raghavan (2025). The
intractability results from Chakraborty & Raghavan (2025) highlight a conundrum: if the capacity of the
network eventually diverges, then should we still aim to continually train AI models? In this paper we
1
demonstrate that the answer to this question is indeed “yes"; in fact, the solution in the presence of diverging
capacity is to reliably change the architecture of the AI model on the fly according to the needs of the data
distribution.
However, two key bottlenecks remain before attaining this goal. (i) Reliably changing the architecture
requires a methodical understanding of “how the tasks, the weights and the architecture of the model
interact with each other." This understanding is dificult to observe with current optimization theory tools
because architecture dependencies are not visible when the problem of continual learning is defined just
over the weights as is done typically Chakraborty & Raghavan (2025); Raghavan & Balaprakash (2021)
or Lu et al. (2025). Recent works such as CLEAS Gao et al. (2022) and SEAL Gambella et al. (2025)
dynamically expand model capacity by adding layers. However, none enables generic architecture changes
such as modifying the number of parameters, activation functions, or layer structure. (ii) The key obstacle is
that a generic change in architecture requires transferring information between parameter spaces of different
dimensions, a problem that remains unsolved.
Contribution: To address these bottlenecks, we develop a comprehensive approach to enhance the theoret-
ical understanding of CL and facilitate practical implementations to allow for joint training of architecture
and weights. Our specific contributions are as follows.
1. Theoretical Contributions: To observe the interplay between tasks, weights and the architecture, we
formulate the problem of continual learning in a Sobolev space where both the architecture and the weights
are treated as learnable parameters, making the coupling between model capacity and distribution shift
amenable to rigorous analysis. Furthermore, we derive necessary conditions for the existence of a CL solution
and prove that adapting weights alone is insufficient to mitigate catastrophic forgetting under distribution
shift; in contrast, jointly adapting the architecture and weights yields strictly tighter error.
2. Empirical Contributions: We develop a low-rank transfer mechanism that maps learned knowledge from
a previous architecture to a new architecture of different dimensionality via learned transformation matri-
ces, enabling generic architecture changes without discarding prior knowledge. We validate our approach
empirically across regression and classification problems using feedforward, convolutional, and graph neural
networks, demonstrating up to two orders of magnitude improvement in training loss, reduced forgetting,
and enhanced robustness to noise compared with static-architecture baselines.
Organization: Section 2 motivates the problem of continual learning and the necessity for function space
modeling. Section 3 formulates neural networks as members of a Sobolev space. Section 4 derives the neces-
sary conditions for the existence of a CL solution and demonstrates that adapting weights alone is insufficient.
Section 5 presents our algorithm for architecture search and low-rank transfer across architectures. Section 6
reviews related work, and Section 7 provides empirical validation.
