For illustration, assume ℓ( ˆf (w(i), ψ, X (i))) is strongly convex. The right side of Fig. 1 depicts level sets
in the parameter space, where each ball represents ℓ( ˆf (w(i), ψ, X (i))) ≤ η and the plus signs denote the
minima for i = 1 and i = 2. For example, on MNIST, the two balls may correspond to digits 0 and 1: the
boundary of each ball represents all parameters achieving cross-entropy loss below η = 1, with the plus sign
at zero loss. Now consider an AI model that trains on digit 0 and achieves the minimum. When digit 1
arrives, the model begins from this minimum, inheriting a bias from the previous task. It must then converge
to a solution that performs well on both tasks, which lies in the intersection of the two balls. Since the size
of this intersection depends on the dissimilarity between tasks, the following theorem is observed.
Theorem 1 Fix the number of weight updates required to obtain the optimal value at each task. Assume
that each subsequent task introduces a value of change into the model with the change described in some
appropriate metric. Let ℓ be the Lipschitz continuous function, and choose a small learning rate. Then,
capacity diverges as a function of the number of tasks. Please see Chakraborty & Raghavan (2025)
for a full statement and its proof.
The theorem implies that the AI model’s ability to successfully represent tasks will deteriorate as more tasks
are introduced when the new tasks are different from the previous one. In such a case, continually training
the AI model is bound to fail if we just update the weights of the network. An intuitive side effect of this
3
theorem is that, the intersection of the two balls in the right of Fig. 1 will shrink as the tasks become more
different, and eventually, the intersection will be empty. In such a case, there is no solution.
In this paper we hypothesize and prove that the size of the intersection space in Fig. 1 can be increased by
modifying the architecture of the AI model, that is, by increasing the number of parameters in the model.
Doing so, however, would require us to model the interplay between the weights, data, and the architecture.
An idea impossible to imagine with the intuition laid out until now because the size of the intersection space
is fixed by the size of the ball and the size of the ball, that is the capacity of the model, is fixed due to
the choice of the architecture. Since the size of the weight space cannot be influenced by looking just at
the weight space and the movement of weights within the weight space, we need alternate mathematical
machinery.




