In Definition 2, D is our data space. For any standard AI application, we can assume that D is a finite
subset of Rn. This is an important practical consideration as, for AI model training to be efficient, one needs
the numerical values of the data to be bounded, typically achieved through normalization as in Huang et al.
(2023). As D is a finite subset of Rn, it is a closed subset. Thus, by Heine–Borel, D is also compact, see
Rudin (1976).
The next assumption we note is the presence of weak derivatives. In a standard neural network, derivatives are
assumed to exist since twice differentiability is necessary for training and typical training involves gradient-
based methods such as Kingma & Ba (2017). In the Sobolev space, the existence of weak derivatives is a
more general condition than the existence of classical derivatives. In particular, weak derivatiuves allow for
functions that may not be differentiable in the classical sense but still have well-defined derivatives in the
weak sense. This is important for the architecture choices as, many of these choices may not be differentiably
in the classical sense, but they are differentiable in the weak sense. For example, the ReLU activation function
is not differentiable at zero, but it has a well-defined weak derivative as discussed in Petersen et al. (2021)
and Adegoke & Layeni (2016).
