Theorem 8 establishes the existence condition for the CL solution of (Cumulative CL); its contrapositive
states that dissimilar loss values imply dissimilar tasks. However, the converse need not hold: for tasks X (t)
and X (t + ∆t) with μ(X (t) △ X (t + ∆t)) ≥ δ, the loss difference |J(w(t), ψ(t), X (t)) − J(w(t + 1), ψ(t +
1), X (t + 1))| may or may not exceed ε. When dissimilar tasks do produce dissimilar losses, increasing the
number of tasks drives |J(w(t), ψ(t), X (t)) − J(w(t + 1), ψ(t + 1), X (t + 1))| beyond ε, causing the model to
progressively forget prior tasks and ultimately violating Theorem 8.
In order to counteract this situation, the key condition for absolute continuity must be upheld; that is, for a
series of tasks, the upper bound on ∑T
