The implications of Theorem 12 indicate that it is
possible to shrink the effect of the new task on the
forgetting cost J by changing the architecture of the
network by pushing ε closer to zero as seen in Fig. 4.
The closer ε is to zero, the more the cardinality of
the intersection space and the more the task sets are
connected. Therefore, upholding the absolute conti-
nuity of J is feasible. It is now of interest to identify
how to change the architecture and efficiently learn
over a series of tasks. In particular, we must ex-
amine to what extent we can control the effect of
architecture change on the CL problem.




As we have established the importance of changing
the architecture to uphold the absolute continuity
of J and therefore ensure the existence of a solution
to (Cumulative CL), we now turn to the question of
how to change the architecture and efficiently learn
over a series of tasks. We begin at task t = 1 and de-
termine an optimal weight denoted w∗(1) = w∞(1).
This gives us a neural network solution in F1 for the
first task. Then, as the next task is observed, we
perform a derivative-free hyperparameter search, in
particular, the directional direct search method Lar-
